The ellipse whose equation is
\[\frac{x^2}{25} + \frac{y^2}{9} = 1\]is graphed below.  The chord $\overline{AB}$ passes through a focus $F$ of the ellipse.  If $AF = \frac{3}{2},$ then find $BF.$

[asy]
unitsize (0.6 cm);

pair A, B, F;

F = (4,0);
A = (35/8,3*sqrt(15)/8);
B = (55/16,-9*sqrt(15)/16);

draw(xscale(5)*yscale(3)*Circle((0,0),1));
draw(A--B);
draw((-6,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-4)--(0,4));

dot("$A$", A, NE);
dot("$B$", B, SE);
dot("$F$", F, NW);
[/asy]

inference:
Let $O$ be the center of the ellipse.  Then $OF = \sqrt{25 - 9} = 4.$  Also, $OA = 5,$ so by the Pythagorean Theorem on triangle $OAF,$
\[AF^2 = OA^2 - OF^2 = 25 - 16 = 9.\]Then $AF = 3.$  Since $AF = \frac{3}{2},$ we must have $F$ located $\frac{1}{2}$ of the way from $A$ to $O.$

[asy]
unitsize (0.6 cm);

pair A, B, F, O;

O = (0,0);
F = (4,0);
A = (35/8,3*sqrt(15)/8);
B = (55/16,-9*sqrt(15)/16);

draw(xscale(5)*yscale(3)*Circle((0,0),1));
draw(A--B);
draw((-6,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-4)--(0,4));
draw(A--F);

dot("$A$", A, NE);
dot("$B$", B, SE);
dot("$F$", F, NW);
dot("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

Since $F$ is a focus, $BF + AF = 2a = 10,$ so $BF = 10 - AF = 10 - \frac{3}{2} = \boxed{\frac{17}{2}}.$

